00:35:59.736 --> 00:36:00.496
Thank you.

594
00:36:02.236 --> 00:36:06.116
I'd like to invite up Dr. Carl Desomme from Washington University

595
00:36:06.836 --> 00:36:10.796
School of Medicine in St. Louis, and he'll be presenting on a novel

596
00:36:10.956 --> 00:36:14.456
first in class chimeric antigen receptor dendritic cell platform driving

597
00:36:14.496 --> 00:36:17.576
broad and durable antitumor immunity in solid tumors.

598
00:36:18.976 --> 00:36:21.296
All right. Well, thank you so much for the opportunity to speak here.

599
00:36:22.796 --> 00:36:26.596
So, the goal of this project, like many projects, is to try to

600
00:36:26.636 --> 00:36:28.576
make difficult cancers more curable.

601
00:36:28.956 --> 00:36:32.916
And I'll talk about a little bit of the limitations of current immune therapies.

602
00:36:33.456 --> 00:36:37.376
The last patient right here is a patient we treated on a Phase I trial with CAR T

603
00:36:37.476 --> 00:36:41.266
cells, ALL, and they had a great response for a while, and then a year later, they

604
00:36:41.276 --> 00:36:44.916
regressed. They progressed and regressed and eventually died.

605
00:36:44.976 --> 00:36:48.056
So I'll talk about the limitations of current cell therapies and other immune

606
00:36:48.096 --> 00:36:51.616
therapies, and then talk about CAR DC1s, which is a

607
00:36:52.176 --> 00:36:55.696
newer method for combining the precision of CAR engineering with

608
00:36:55.836 --> 00:36:58.856
dendritic cell immune orchestration, and then talk a little bit about the

609
00:36:58.896 --> 00:37:01.576
manufacturing of this new type of cell

610
00:37:01.636 --> 00:37:04.776
therapy.So CAR T cells we know

611
00:37:05.196 --> 00:37:08.886
encounter many limitations in solid tumors. One of them is antigen escape.

612
00:37:09.226 --> 00:37:13.156
If there's antigen negative tumor cells, then those eventually progress, and there

613
00:37:13.196 --> 00:37:16.676
are almost always antigen negative tumor cells in solid tumors, and that alone

614
00:37:16.776 --> 00:37:20.746
accounts for many of the lack of complete responses we see in

615
00:37:20.816 --> 00:37:21.646
solid tumors, I think.

616
00:37:22.656 --> 00:37:24.776
When you think about PD-1 inhibitor therapy,

617
00:37:25.836 --> 00:37:26.056
the

618
00:37:26.936 --> 00:37:30.856
anti-PD-1 therapy requires activated tumor reactive T cells in the

619
00:37:30.896 --> 00:37:32.076
beginning for those

620
00:37:33.076 --> 00:37:36.936
PD-1 inhibitors to work upon, and specifically those in a stem-like state or a PEC

621
00:37:37.056 --> 00:37:40.596
state. And it's really unclear how to generate these T cells in a patient who does

622
00:37:40.636 --> 00:37:44.356
not already have them, and especially antigen-specific stem-like T cells.

623
00:37:45.176 --> 00:37:48.096
But we do know from mouse studies that they require priming by DC1s.

624
00:37:48.676 --> 00:37:51.576
So DC1s are really the generals of the immune system.

625
00:37:51.956 --> 00:37:55.436
They create T cell responses and B cell responses, and they do

626
00:37:55.496 --> 00:37:58.976
that primarily by sensing infected

627
00:37:59.016 --> 00:38:02.946
cells. Over evolution, they've really evolved to

628
00:38:02.946 --> 00:38:06.276
detect infected cells, and they take up those infected fragments,

629
00:38:06.676 --> 00:38:10.586
migrate to draining lymph nodes, and then cross prime T cells, create memory, and

630
00:38:10.656 --> 00:38:11.496
affect your cells that way.

631
00:38:12.316 --> 00:38:16.076
They can also do this in cancer, but one glaring difference in cancer is that tumor

632
00:38:16.136 --> 00:38:19.996
cells don't express the pattern recognition receptors that an affected cell

633
00:38:20.056 --> 00:38:23.906
has. So there is nothing that distinctively tells a dendritic

634
00:38:23.956 --> 00:38:27.656
cell that a tumor is a foreign cell that needs to be reacted

635
00:38:27.676 --> 00:38:31.136
upon. So we thought this was a good opportunity for a chimeric antigen

636
00:38:31.176 --> 00:38:35.096
receptor. Unfortunately, it took a long time to engineer type one dendritic

637
00:38:35.136 --> 00:38:36.506
cells. It turns out they're very hard to engineer.

638
00:38:36.596 --> 00:38:40.526
But we eventually were able to identify CARs that

639
00:38:40.556 --> 00:38:43.016
expressed very highly on the surface of these cells.

640
00:38:43.046 --> 00:38:45.936
And for the dendritic cell aficionados, this is what they look like.

641
00:38:45.976 --> 00:38:49.926
They're really type one dendritic cells, XCR1 high, SIRPalpha low.

642
00:38:51.156 --> 00:38:54.876
And these are delivered with an mRNA, so it's a non-integrating technology.

643
00:38:55.856 --> 00:38:59.516
It's structured like a normal CAR antibody domain linker, transmembrane signaling

644
00:38:59.556 --> 00:39:03.106
domain, and then a cleavage site with a co-expression marker of Thy1.1.

645
00:39:03.976 --> 00:39:07.376
We're targeting B7-H3 as the tumor antigen here because it's on a wide range of

646
00:39:07.436 --> 00:39:11.396
solid tumors. And then for controls, we have the binding only domain, which

647
00:39:11.416 --> 00:39:14.436
doesn't have the signaling domain, and then Thy1 alone.

648
00:39:14.476 --> 00:39:16.536
And we've tested a number of different signaling domains.

649
00:39:16.576 --> 00:39:20.336
I'm going to talk about the TLR4 signaling domain because it's really a receptor

650
00:39:20.396 --> 00:39:24.236
that recognizes infections and has a robust response

651
00:39:24.276 --> 00:39:25.796
against infections normally.

652
00:39:27.156 --> 00:39:31.056
So first we noticed that when we engineer these DC1s with a CAR, with the TLR4

653
00:39:31.136 --> 00:39:34.036
signaling domain, they take up more antigen.

654
00:39:34.156 --> 00:39:35.896
So if you

655
00:39:36.856 --> 00:39:40.436
express OVA, that's AF488 labeled in the tumor,

656
00:39:40.856 --> 00:39:41.576
co-culture them

657
00:39:42.396 --> 00:39:46.336
with these CAR DC1s, you see greater uptake of OVA

658
00:39:46.376 --> 00:39:49.336
from the tumor. The binding only DCs also take up more.

659
00:39:49.396 --> 00:39:53.176
So just forcing the interaction between the DC1 and the tumor

660
00:39:53.516 --> 00:39:57.036
allows the DCs to acquire more antigen, but more is required when there's

661
00:39:57.076 --> 00:39:57.976
TLR4 signaling.

662
00:39:59.236 --> 00:40:03.176
And more dramatically, the costimulatory program is

663
00:40:03.216 --> 00:40:05.296
really strongly driven by TLR4 signaling.

664
00:40:05.356 --> 00:40:08.316
So with the binding only DCs, as you would imagine, they don't have any

665
00:40:08.436 --> 00:40:12.376
signaling domain. They don't induce expression of

666
00:40:12.436 --> 00:40:16.196
things like CCR7, 4-1BB ligand, CD86, CD70.

667
00:40:16.496 --> 00:40:19.876
However, the TLR4 signaling CARs really induce a strong

668
00:40:19.896 --> 00:40:23.596
costimulatory program across many different costimulatory

669
00:40:23.636 --> 00:40:24.096
molecules.

670
00:40:26.076 --> 00:40:29.666
Now in vitro, we do this cross-priming assay, which is a really nice assay to look

671
00:40:29.696 --> 00:40:33.236
for the ability of the DC to cross-prime tumor reactive T cells.

672
00:40:33.656 --> 00:40:37.436
And for these we use oval loaded tumor that expresses B7H3.

673
00:40:37.976 --> 00:40:41.636
It has MHC-1 knocked out on its own cells, so it can't directly

674
00:40:41.646 --> 00:40:45.636
stimulate T cells. And so the only way to stimulate these OT-1

675
00:40:45.676 --> 00:40:48.666
T cells is through antigen uptake and then

676
00:40:48.676 --> 00:40:51.996
processing and presentation on the DC's own MHC-1.

677
00:40:52.586 --> 00:40:54.636
And then we look at proliferation and activation.

678
00:40:56.116 --> 00:40:59.996
And we like to also do this with wild type T cells because ideally we don't want to

679
00:41:00.076 --> 00:41:03.496
activate all T cells in the body. We don't want to create toxicity.

680
00:41:03.536 --> 00:41:07.066
We really want to activate the tumor specific T cells, which is a really hard thing

681
00:41:07.136 --> 00:41:07.396
to do.

682
00:41:08.996 --> 00:41:10.196
So when you look at this

683
00:41:11.316 --> 00:41:15.196
proliferation, which is CTV here, and then CD44 expression, which is a

684
00:41:15.236 --> 00:41:18.416
measure of activation, the wild type T cells in this circumstance get very

685
00:41:18.456 --> 00:41:21.876
minimally activated. But the tumor specific T cells are very, very substantially

686
00:41:21.896 --> 00:41:23.076
activated. This is a three-day assay.

687
00:41:23.675 --> 00:41:27.336
And when you quantify this, you can see 1,000-fold

688
00:41:27.396 --> 00:41:31.116
increase in the activation of tumor specific T cells versus wild type T

689
00:41:31.196 --> 00:41:31.516
cells.

690
00:41:32.376 --> 00:41:36.056
And the normal DCs, Thy1 DCs, binding only

691
00:41:36.096 --> 00:41:39.196
DCs, have a very, very small

692
00:41:40.076 --> 00:41:43.596
activity compared to the CAR DCs. So if you blew up the access, this would be a

693
00:41:43.636 --> 00:41:46.696
significant difference, but it's not nearly as big as the CAR.

694
00:41:48.536 --> 00:41:50.436
So jumping ahead into solid tumor models.

695
00:41:50.476 --> 00:41:54.436
So this is a sarcoma, MCA-induced sarcoma syngeneic model, BL6

696
00:41:54.476 --> 00:41:58.236
mice, and 75% of the tumor cells here express

697
00:41:58.276 --> 00:42:01.556
B7H3. 25% of them are B7H3 negative.

698
00:42:01.606 --> 00:42:04.146
So we do this to model the heterogeneity seen in patients.

699
00:42:04.686 --> 00:42:07.676
And there's no exogenous tumor antigens here, so there's no OVA, there's no

700
00:42:07.756 --> 00:42:10.006
overexpressed antigen that

701
00:42:11.756 --> 00:42:13.416
makes it easier for T cells to eliminate.

702
00:42:14.256 --> 00:42:18.196
And so when we treat these with Thy1 mRNA modified

703
00:42:18.676 --> 00:42:19.696
DCs, you get

704
00:42:20.696 --> 00:42:22.136
a couple of rejections out of 30 mice.

705
00:42:22.636 --> 00:42:26.096
Binding only DCs do a little bit better of a job, but

706
00:42:26.156 --> 00:42:29.836
the TLR4 signaling CAR DCs really have a pretty

707
00:42:29.916 --> 00:42:32.196
striking complete rejection rate, 30 out of 30 mice.

708
00:42:32.616 --> 00:42:36.056
And I think this is when we first started to think this is potentially going to be

709
00:42:36.196 --> 00:42:36.316
a

710
00:42:37.416 --> 00:42:41.156
great way to possibly treat solid tumors if we can harness this,

711
00:42:41.296 --> 00:42:42.436
especially in the clinical setting.

712
00:42:43.636 --> 00:42:44.276
So when we

713
00:42:45.836 --> 00:42:49.396
take these mice that have been cured and we re-inject them with new tumor 100 days

714
00:42:49.436 --> 00:42:52.836
later, so far after the time that the DCs are gone, if we re-inject a

715
00:42:52.856 --> 00:42:56.596
B7H3 positive tumor or B7H3 negative tumor, you get a

716
00:42:56.656 --> 00:43:00.036
similar rejection of the tumor late on.

717
00:43:00.116 --> 00:43:03.876
So there's long-term memory, and that memory is against antigens that are not the

718
00:43:03.916 --> 00:43:07.796
CAR targets. Remember, the CAR DC is targeting B7H3, but it creates a T

719
00:43:07.876 --> 00:43:11.256
cell response against non-B7H3

720
00:43:11.316 --> 00:43:15.126
antigens.So we wanted to know these antigens that are

721
00:43:16.726 --> 00:43:20.386
reacting, and the T cells that are reacting to these antigens, how is this working?

722
00:43:20.746 --> 00:43:24.666
We looked at OVA, but we all know OVA is a artificial antigen, it

723
00:43:24.686 --> 00:43:27.586
has a high affinity TCR. You can overexpress at high levels.

724
00:43:27.646 --> 00:43:29.786
So what happens to the endogenous tumor antigens?

725
00:43:30.566 --> 00:43:32.066
So to answer this, we did a

726
00:43:33.266 --> 00:43:36.986
number of mass spec analyses where we looked at the cross-presented

727
00:43:37.026 --> 00:43:40.946
peptides on CAR DC1s and elute the

728
00:43:41.026 --> 00:43:45.006
MHC-1 peptides and quantify them

729
00:43:45.046 --> 00:43:48.626
by mass spec to identify what are the peptides that are actually being

730
00:43:48.666 --> 00:43:51.566
cross-presented by CAR DC1's endogenous peptides.

731
00:43:52.926 --> 00:43:56.646
And this is a log 2 scale, but you can see that the total cross-presented

732
00:43:56.706 --> 00:44:00.486
peptide abundance is far greater with CAR DC1s compared to the

733
00:44:00.506 --> 00:44:01.366
binding-only DCs

734
00:44:02.346 --> 00:44:06.126
and compared to the Thy1 DCs. So just like the OVA experiments,

735
00:44:06.226 --> 00:44:10.196
they do cross present a large amount of peptides, and many of those

736
00:44:10.206 --> 00:44:14.006
peptides are actually unique. So these are peptides that are not cross-presented

737
00:44:14.086 --> 00:44:16.645
at all by normal DCs. So this potentially

738
00:44:17.446 --> 00:44:20.886
allows the DCs to create T cell responses that weren't potentially

739
00:44:21.306 --> 00:44:23.506
there with normal DC responses.

740
00:44:24.986 --> 00:44:28.626
When you look at the individual peptides, you can see that a

741
00:44:28.686 --> 00:44:32.646
normal DC cross-presents peptides from the tumor at a wide array

742
00:44:32.666 --> 00:44:35.006
of levels. Many of them are at very low levels.

743
00:44:35.056 --> 00:44:38.866
The CAR DC really cross-presents peptides at a very high level, almost across the

744
00:44:38.886 --> 00:44:42.406
board. 90% of the peptides here are cross-presented at a level that's higher than

745
00:44:42.446 --> 00:44:44.606
the average DC is cross-presenting peptides.

746
00:44:45.086 --> 00:44:48.906
So you get not only a larger repertoire, but a higher abundance

747
00:44:49.046 --> 00:44:51.446
and expression of these cross-presented peptides.

748
00:44:52.886 --> 00:44:55.646
So this tells us a number of things are cross-presented, but it doesn't actually

749
00:44:55.766 --> 00:44:59.266
tell us are any of these cross-presented peptides actually creating T cell

750
00:44:59.306 --> 00:45:02.126
responses and are these T cell

751
00:45:02.226 --> 00:45:05.426
responses being affected by the CAR DC?

752
00:45:05.486 --> 00:45:07.606
Is the phenotype of those T cells changing?

753
00:45:08.746 --> 00:45:12.176
A lot of those questions we then sought to answer with a number of other

754
00:45:12.176 --> 00:45:14.646
experiments that I'll try to condense down to a couple slides here.

755
00:45:15.406 --> 00:45:18.926
But so the first question is, new epitopes

756
00:45:19.466 --> 00:45:22.906
are easiest to look at because we know that they're not present in normal tissues.

757
00:45:23.286 --> 00:45:26.866
So if we can find new antigen-specific responses, then those are

758
00:45:26.906 --> 00:45:30.446
easiest to track. So we took our sarcoma, and

759
00:45:30.506 --> 00:45:34.006
we predicted new antigens, new epitopes, and we

760
00:45:34.646 --> 00:45:38.606
found 176 predicted antigens that could bind MHC-1 within the

761
00:45:38.646 --> 00:45:42.006
tumor. When we actually did mass spec on the tumor cells, we only could find

762
00:45:42.146 --> 00:45:46.126
three of these new antigens were actually expressed by the tumor cells on their

763
00:45:46.146 --> 00:45:46.766
own MHC-1.

764
00:45:47.726 --> 00:45:51.666
So then we looked at the CAR DCs, and we found that they cross-presented

765
00:45:51.706 --> 00:45:55.226
all three of those neoantigens. And the first

766
00:45:55.246 --> 00:45:58.866
neoantigen is here. You can see the binding-only DCs cross-presented it very

767
00:45:58.906 --> 00:46:01.606
poorly. CAR DCs cross-presented it much better.

768
00:46:01.756 --> 00:46:04.486
The second of these was cross-presented pretty poorly by both of them.

769
00:46:05.146 --> 00:46:07.666
And then third was cross-presented fairly highly by both of them.

770
00:46:07.746 --> 00:46:11.296
So we decided this is a neoantigen we would look at, and it was

771
00:46:11.296 --> 00:46:14.376
cross-presented at similar levels in the wild-type DCs and the CAR DCs.

772
00:46:14.706 --> 00:46:18.235
So we wanted to know, are there actual T cells reacting to that

773
00:46:18.246 --> 00:46:21.986
neoantigen? What is the phenotype of those T cells?

774
00:46:22.016 --> 00:46:25.266
So we used that neoantigen to make tetramers, and then we stained

775
00:46:25.346 --> 00:46:28.735
the TILS for T cells that react against

776
00:46:28.766 --> 00:46:31.696
that. And we found that indeed there are T cells that react against this

777
00:46:31.706 --> 00:46:34.826
neoantigen, and indeed, the CAR DCs

778
00:46:35.386 --> 00:46:38.746
increase the number of TILS that are responsive to this neoantigen,

779
00:46:39.246 --> 00:46:40.746
both in the tumor and in the spleen.

780
00:46:41.486 --> 00:46:45.366
Consistent with the idea that the T cells are being primed in the lymph

781
00:46:45.386 --> 00:46:48.496
node and then circulating systemically, taking up residence in the spleen and also

782
00:46:48.526 --> 00:46:51.246
going to the tumor. When we looked at the

783
00:46:52.066 --> 00:46:53.526
phenotype of these

784
00:46:54.326 --> 00:46:56.806
tumor-specific T cells, we noticed that they were all different.

785
00:46:56.946 --> 00:47:00.706
They were also different from that of T cells

786
00:47:00.716 --> 00:47:03.086
primed by wild-type dendritic cells.

787
00:47:03.146 --> 00:47:06.926
So in particular, they expressed low tox and high

788
00:47:06.966 --> 00:47:10.586
PD-1, and this is this transitory effector cell that was actually just discussed in

789
00:47:10.626 --> 00:47:11.146
the last talk.

790
00:47:12.466 --> 00:47:16.386
And this is an interesting population because it's in many different studies shown

791
00:47:16.406 --> 00:47:20.166
to be a very important population for T cell mediated tumor

792
00:47:20.226 --> 00:47:22.366
killing and lasting immune responses.

793
00:47:23.086 --> 00:47:26.946
We also know from the literature that this population generally comes from a

794
00:47:27.006 --> 00:47:30.786
stem-like T cell population, and that stem-like T cell population generally lives

795
00:47:30.846 --> 00:47:32.426
outside of the tumor where there's no antigen.

796
00:47:32.486 --> 00:47:36.346
So we looked at the tumor-draining lymph nodes and the

797
00:47:36.366 --> 00:47:39.766
phenotype of the T cells there. And consistent with that, we see very high

798
00:47:39.786 --> 00:47:43.386
expression of things like TCF1, TCF7, this gene,

799
00:47:43.826 --> 00:47:47.326
SLAMF6, IL7 receptor, Bcl-2. And this is

800
00:47:47.746 --> 00:47:51.546
really generating a stem-like T cell signature within the tumor-draining lymph

801
00:47:51.566 --> 00:47:51.766
node.

802
00:47:52.906 --> 00:47:56.626
So the CAR DC1s are not only generating more tumor-reactive T cells, they're also

803
00:47:56.686 --> 00:48:00.266
generating a stem-like population in the tumor-draining lymph node.

804
00:48:00.366 --> 00:48:04.246
And these stem-like T cells are known to be

805
00:48:04.286 --> 00:48:07.976
able to continuously repopulate the tumor with

806
00:48:08.006 --> 00:48:11.926
new waves of effector cells. So to test that functionality here, we

807
00:48:11.966 --> 00:48:15.946
took those tumor-draining lymph nodes, the CD8 T cells from the tumor-draining

808
00:48:15.986 --> 00:48:19.946
lymph nodes, and then injected them into new Rag mice that had tumor and

809
00:48:20.006 --> 00:48:23.986
looked for the ability of these progenitors that had produced a

810
00:48:24.006 --> 00:48:27.986
wave of response in the primary tumor to produce a new wave of response

811
00:48:28.006 --> 00:48:31.106
in the secondary tumor. And if you do this in untreated mice,

812
00:48:31.986 --> 00:48:35.496
just for reference, you get very few clones that can

813
00:48:35.546 --> 00:48:38.846
repopulate or create these recall competent T cells.

814
00:48:38.906 --> 00:48:42.886
Most of them cannot continuously repopulate the tumor with new effector cells.

815
00:48:43.906 --> 00:48:45.466
We also labeled these with cell trace violet.

816
00:48:45.526 --> 00:48:49.466
So we know that 100% of these cells have proliferated, so

817
00:48:49.486 --> 00:48:52.526
they weren't the cells we actually transferred, but these are the progeny.

818
00:48:52.946 --> 00:48:56.246
So this is the original tumor. And after CAR DC1 treatment,

819
00:48:56.746 --> 00:48:58.906
most of these tumor-draining T cells

820
00:49:00.166 --> 00:49:02.666
can produce new progeny that continuously

821
00:49:03.226 --> 00:49:06.986
reinfiltrate the tumor. So you can see also the numbers,

822
00:49:07.446 --> 00:49:11.016
but the repertoire is affected. When we look back at the

823
00:49:11.446 --> 00:49:15.106
neoantigen-specific T cell repertoire, you can see that there's both a

824
00:49:15.146 --> 00:49:18.785
greater diversity and a greater number of these antigen-specific T

825
00:49:18.826 --> 00:49:22.654
cells.And I want to go back and just point out that

826
00:49:22.694 --> 00:49:26.354
these are just T cells that react against a single neoantigen.

827
00:49:26.554 --> 00:49:29.794
So there's over 100 different clones that recognize this

828
00:49:29.814 --> 00:49:33.754
single neoantigen. This is only one antigen out of all of

829
00:49:33.794 --> 00:49:37.134
these that was cross-presented by the CAR DC1.

830
00:49:37.214 --> 00:49:41.174
So when we think about antigen heterogeneity and overcoming that, I think

831
00:49:41.234 --> 00:49:45.134
that this is potentially explaining why we get this very nice response

832
00:49:45.154 --> 00:49:47.314
against heterogeneous tumors.

833
00:49:49.074 --> 00:49:52.194
So limitation of current cell therapy, single antigen targeting

834
00:49:52.533 --> 00:49:54.854
inevitably leads to resistance in many cases.

835
00:49:55.334 --> 00:49:57.994
This is an ability to enable

836
00:49:58.454 --> 00:50:01.454
multi-antigen capture and cross-presentation to T cells.

837
00:50:01.894 --> 00:50:04.694
It's a way to orchestrate the full cancer immune cycle,

838
00:50:05.894 --> 00:50:09.654
as you can see in the T cell phenotype in the repertoire that develops.

839
00:50:10.614 --> 00:50:13.724
And we think that this is particularly well designed to treat solid tumors,

840
00:50:13.814 --> 00:50:16.494
although it could certainly be a liquid tumor treatment as well.

841
00:50:17.834 --> 00:50:18.454
So the next

842
00:50:19.434 --> 00:50:20.694
big process in this whole

843
00:50:22.354 --> 00:50:26.214
many year project was really trying to create a human CAR

844
00:50:26.254 --> 00:50:29.994
DC1 therapy. DC1s have traditionally been hard to generate in large numbers

845
00:50:30.054 --> 00:50:33.184
in human cells, so we utilized this

846
00:50:33.314 --> 00:50:37.254
AI-enabled synthetic agonist method that allows us to create

847
00:50:37.294 --> 00:50:38.074
a cocktail of

848
00:50:39.374 --> 00:50:41.594
synthetic cytokines that really

849
00:50:42.574 --> 00:50:46.174
pretty potently commit human hematopoietic stem cells to the conventional

850
00:50:46.214 --> 00:50:50.154
DC1 lineage. And we do this in a closed system in conjunction

851
00:50:50.174 --> 00:50:53.194
with Fisher Scientific and are able to manufacture

852
00:50:53.994 --> 00:50:57.954
over 300 million CAR DC1s per run. And this is a clinical

853
00:50:58.274 --> 00:51:02.034
grade production process that's scalable and ready for the GMP

854
00:51:02.074 --> 00:51:05.974
setting. What it can mean for patients, obviously, is

855
00:51:06.634 --> 00:51:09.054
we could potentially treat tumors that are resistant to current therapies,

856
00:51:09.394 --> 00:51:12.934
eliminate tumors more completely, reduce relapse, create

857
00:51:12.974 --> 00:51:16.804
long-term protection, and expand to cell types that are B7-H3 positive,

858
00:51:17.254 --> 00:51:19.214
of which there are many solid tumor cell

859
00:51:20.234 --> 00:51:24.074
types that have a high expression B7-H3, and conceivably other

860
00:51:24.094 --> 00:51:25.154
antigens should work too. We

861
00:51:26.014 --> 00:51:29.714
just are pursuing B7-H3 at the moment.

862
00:51:30.263 --> 00:51:33.794
The program status currently in the path forward,

863
00:51:34.254 --> 00:51:38.214
so the first in human clinical trial is funded and planning for

864
00:51:38.354 --> 00:51:42.074
2027, and we'll start out with intra-tumoral delivery

865
00:51:42.994 --> 00:51:46.923
as a safety phase and then move to IV delivery, which we've also done in mice as

866
00:51:46.974 --> 00:51:49.454
well and is the goal of the therapy in the long run.

867
00:51:50.434 --> 00:51:53.734
It's currently being advanced completely within the academic center, but we think

868
00:51:53.794 --> 00:51:54.394
it's also

869
00:51:55.514 --> 00:51:59.454
potentially a useful strategic partnering

870
00:51:59.534 --> 00:52:02.174
opportunity if we want to potentially expand the platform.

871
00:52:02.514 --> 00:52:05.994
Right now we're seeking to treat a select few group of

872
00:52:07.014 --> 00:52:07.594
malignancies.

873
00:52:09.414 --> 00:52:12.294
So I'd like to thank the people who do the work in this lab,

874
00:52:13.654 --> 00:52:17.574
and then our collaborators and our funders and

875
00:52:17.934 --> 00:52:21.854
collaborators at Fisher for the human translational product as well.

876
00:52:22.754 --> 00:52:24.974
And I'd be happy to take any questions.

877
00:52:31.414 --> 00:52:34.923
Thank you, Dr. Dassome. In interest of time, we'll hold

878
00:52:34.974 --> 00:52:36.414
questions and move on to the next talk.

879
00:52:36.454 --> 00:52:38.363
I mean, afterwards, if you have any thoughts.

880
00:52:40.363 --> 00:52:44.034
All right. Next we'll welcome Dr. Sabine

881
00:52:44.114 --> 00:52:47.914
Heiteneider from Stanford University, and she'll be

882
00:52:48.554 --> 00:52:50.934
discussing "Decoding the Medulloblastoma

883
00:52:51.014 --> 00:52:54.474
Serpinosome Prioritizes the

884
00:52:54.534 --> 00:52:58.294
Oncofetal Antigen GPC2 for Potent CAR T

885
00:52:58.394 --> 00:52:59.034
Cell Therapy."

886
00:53:01.034 --> 00:53:03.214
Thank you very much for the kind introduction.

887
00:53:03.254 --> 00:53:05.634
That was an excellent pronunciation of my last name.

888
00:53:06.554 --> 00:53:10.274
I'm excited to have this opportunity today to speak to you about our

889
00:53:10.314 --> 00:53:14.214
hunt for ideal target antigens for childhood solid tumors

890
00:53:14.234 --> 00:53:16.643
and brain tumors for CAR T cell therapy.

891
00:53:20.754 --> 00:53:21.934
Okay, these are my disclosures.

892
00:53:22.874 --> 00:53:26.574
So today we really have a clear and growing body of evidence that CAR T

893
00:53:26.694 --> 00:53:30.354
cells can mediate significant clinical

894
00:53:30.394 --> 00:53:32.314
responses in solid tumors and brain tumors.

895
00:53:32.344 --> 00:53:36.194
And to name just a few example, IL-15 armored GPC3

896
00:53:36.234 --> 00:53:39.974
CAR T cells have been reported to

897
00:53:41.354 --> 00:53:44.974
mediate clinical activity in a trial at Texas

898
00:53:45.054 --> 00:53:45.474
Children's.

899
00:53:46.874 --> 00:53:50.754
The Locatelli Group in Italy has reported a 33% complete response

900
00:53:50.834 --> 00:53:54.654
rate in recurrent and refractory neuroblastoma with GD2 CAR T

901
00:53:54.714 --> 00:53:58.604
cells, and our very own institution has written a tremendous

902
00:53:58.674 --> 00:54:00.734
success story of GD2 CAR T cells

903
00:54:02.074 --> 00:54:05.464
in patients with diffuse midline glioma, which is a very aggressive

904
00:54:05.574 --> 00:54:06.954
childhood brain tumor.

905
00:54:08.194 --> 00:54:11.854
And 36% of patients in this trial have experienced tumor volume

906
00:54:11.894 --> 00:54:15.664
reductions of more than 50%, and this included a complete

907
00:54:15.934 --> 00:54:19.434
response that is now actually ongoing for more than four years.

908
00:54:19.474 --> 00:54:19.864
So I think

909
00:54:20.874 --> 00:54:24.364
the time really has passed where CAR T cells are only

910
00:54:24.394 --> 00:54:27.664
applicable for hematologic malignancies, but we still

911
00:54:27.794 --> 00:54:29.854
have barriers to overcome.

912
00:54:31.114 --> 00:54:33.434
So what are some of the key factors to this success?

913
00:54:33.534 --> 00:54:36.974
One that my lab is thinking about extensively are tumor

914
00:54:37.034 --> 00:54:40.594
antigens that in solid tumors and brain tumors can be

915
00:54:40.634 --> 00:54:43.074
targeted with high potency without normal tissue

916
00:54:43.134 --> 00:54:46.234
liability. And one compelling

917
00:54:46.294 --> 00:54:50.144
approach to look for them is to simply take data sets from

918
00:54:50.214 --> 00:54:54.144
all healthy tissues throughout the body and pediatric cancer tissues, and

919
00:54:54.174 --> 00:54:57.114
then simply ask the question, "What's really high on the tumor and what's not on

920
00:54:57.174 --> 00:54:57.834
normal tissues?"

921
00:54:59.114 --> 00:55:03.014
And specifically in childhood cancer, I think we have a compelling opportunity

922
00:55:03.074 --> 00:55:06.654
here due to its prenatal origin. So a lot of childhood

923
00:55:06.754 --> 00:55:10.674
cancers actually resemble fetal transcriptional programs,

924
00:55:11.214 --> 00:55:15.074
and some of the oncogenic events occur during fetal development.

925
00:55:16.454 --> 00:55:19.314
So in that sense, childhood cancers are poised to express

926
00:55:20.154 --> 00:55:24.084
oncofetal antigens that are expressed in developing tissues but then get shut

927
00:55:24.114 --> 00:55:28.054
down at birth, and they represent a compelling opportunity for potent and

928
00:55:28.094 --> 00:55:31.684
safe CAR T targeting.So we did a principal

929
00:55:31.724 --> 00:55:35.664
components analysis, and we looked at pediatric tumor

930
00:55:35.724 --> 00:55:38.944
transcriptomes and compared them to prenatal

931
00:55:39.724 --> 00:55:43.524
healthy brain tissues. And we found that specifically CNS and branul

932
00:55:43.544 --> 00:55:47.444
tumors with ETMR and medulloblastoma here

933
00:55:47.664 --> 00:55:48.364
leading the rank,

934
00:55:49.244 --> 00:55:50.144
closely resemble

935
00:55:51.204 --> 00:55:53.144
prenatal brain tissues.

936
00:55:54.584 --> 00:55:55.304
So we

937
00:55:56.204 --> 00:55:59.904
attempted to decode the surfaceome of medulloblastoma and did a

938
00:55:59.944 --> 00:56:03.924
differential gene expression analysis from transcriptomes of tumors

939
00:56:04.004 --> 00:56:07.744
compared to normal tissues using cell surface filtration, and we found

940
00:56:07.804 --> 00:56:11.144
several significantly upregulated genes in medulloblastoma.

941
00:56:12.184 --> 00:56:15.664
This analysis ranked GPC2 or glypican 2 as the top

942
00:56:15.924 --> 00:56:19.764
candidate, and it actually scored significantly higher than several

943
00:56:19.824 --> 00:56:23.704
other antigens that have been previously described as CAR T targets in

944
00:56:23.724 --> 00:56:24.624
medulloblastoma.

945
00:56:25.504 --> 00:56:29.004
We also identified four additional targets that are compelling

946
00:56:29.064 --> 00:56:32.504
candidates that pass these three predefined filters to look for

947
00:56:32.644 --> 00:56:33.884
suitable CAR antigens.

948
00:56:34.804 --> 00:56:38.474
And interestingly, they actually all follow this oncofetal expression pattern,

949
00:56:38.544 --> 00:56:42.324
where they're expressed at high levels in prenatal tissues but then get shut down

950
00:56:42.384 --> 00:56:43.144
prior to birth.

951
00:56:45.084 --> 00:56:49.074
GPC2 is one antigen that was discovered by surfaceome

952
00:56:49.144 --> 00:56:52.324
profiling of neuroblastoma at the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia.

953
00:56:53.684 --> 00:56:56.504
And when we looked at the transcriptional profiles

954
00:56:57.904 --> 00:57:01.884
during human organ development, we found that GPC2 is a prototypical

955
00:57:01.944 --> 00:57:05.604
oncofetal antigen. So it's expressed at high levels in the developing brain

956
00:57:06.264 --> 00:57:08.824
and cerebellum but gets shut down prior to birth.

957
00:57:09.864 --> 00:57:13.744
This is also resembled in prenatal brain sections, where the

958
00:57:14.864 --> 00:57:18.364
expression of GPC2 declines over time with gestational age,

959
00:57:19.804 --> 00:57:22.484
but it stays high in neuroblastoma tumor sections.

960
00:57:24.124 --> 00:57:26.544
So when we set out to engineer CAR T cells, first,

961
00:57:27.504 --> 00:57:31.324
I attempted to measure the actual antigen density on clinical samples of

962
00:57:31.364 --> 00:57:34.984
neuroblastoma metastatic to the bone marrow and found that they

963
00:57:35.344 --> 00:57:39.084
express only moderate levels of GPC2, so only 5,000 molecules per

964
00:57:39.124 --> 00:57:42.744
cell. And so specifically using these preclinical models

965
00:57:42.984 --> 00:57:46.924
that resemble clinical levels of GPC2, we observed

966
00:57:46.964 --> 00:57:50.704
that CD28-derived transmembrane domains were necessary

967
00:57:51.104 --> 00:57:54.784
to render CAR T cells potent against these clinically relevant

968
00:57:54.864 --> 00:57:55.784
levels of antigen.

969
00:57:56.984 --> 00:57:59.944
And our lead candidate also has a CD28

970
00:58:00.224 --> 00:58:02.444
costimulatory domain to further improve

971
00:58:03.704 --> 00:58:05.724
the antigen detection threshold.

972
00:58:06.604 --> 00:58:10.404
We found that this led to impressive antitumor activity in

973
00:58:10.424 --> 00:58:12.124
preclinical models of neuroblastoma.

974
00:58:12.724 --> 00:58:16.324
However, we found a small fraction of tumors that ended up

975
00:58:16.384 --> 00:58:18.524
recurring after a prolonged interval of cure.

976
00:58:19.204 --> 00:58:22.864
And this was associated with a drop in GPC2 antigen density.

977
00:58:24.184 --> 00:58:27.924
And so to address this problem, we utilized a method that was developed in

978
00:58:27.964 --> 00:58:31.704
Chris Romero's lab and overexpressed the AP1 transcription

979
00:58:31.713 --> 00:58:32.544
factor c-Jun,

980
00:58:33.364 --> 00:58:36.424
which was shown to not only be able to render CAR T cells

981
00:58:36.444 --> 00:58:39.534
exhaustion-resistant, but also further lower the antigen detection

982
00:58:39.604 --> 00:58:43.024
threshold. And this approach indeed mitigated this

983
00:58:43.104 --> 00:58:44.624
antigen-low tumor escape.

984
00:58:46.284 --> 00:58:49.844
In medulloblastoma, GPC2 is expressed at high levels in

985
00:58:49.864 --> 00:58:52.184
transcriptomes across all molecular subgroups.

986
00:58:52.764 --> 00:58:54.564
It's expressed in clinical

987
00:58:56.624 --> 00:59:00.584
specimens of fixed tissue sections skewed towards Group 3 and Group

988
00:59:00.764 --> 00:59:03.864
4, which are the more aggressive subtypes.

989
00:59:03.894 --> 00:59:07.524
We find it in medulloblastoma cell lines, and next developed an

990
00:59:07.584 --> 00:59:11.184
antigen density quantification method to actually measure the

991
00:59:11.224 --> 00:59:14.944
molecules per cell found on medulloblastoma tumor resections,

992
00:59:15.484 --> 00:59:18.964
and compared that to several other target antigens that have been

993
00:59:19.064 --> 00:59:22.484
considered for targeting medulloblastoma.

994
00:59:23.644 --> 00:59:27.454
We found that very similar to our computational pipeline,

995
00:59:27.904 --> 00:59:31.824
thyrotropin receptor alpha, EPHA2, and HER2 only showed limited

996
00:59:31.834 --> 00:59:33.544
expression in clinical samples.

997
00:59:34.844 --> 00:59:37.184
B7H3 was highly prevalent on tumor cells.

998
00:59:37.264 --> 00:59:41.174
However, the antigen density was on the lower end, with

999
00:59:41.204 --> 00:59:43.944
less than 10,000 molecules per cell in the clinical samples.

1000
00:59:45.124 --> 00:59:48.884
For GD2, we actually saw an interesting trend where

1001
00:59:49.304 --> 00:59:53.004
it was very heterogeneous on cell lines, but we found a high and homogeneous

1002
00:59:53.064 --> 00:59:54.564
expression in clinical samples.

1003
00:59:55.884 --> 00:59:59.624
And for GPC2, we also found high fractions of antigen-positive tumor

1004
00:59:59.644 --> 01:00:03.444
cells with an average of more than 6,000 molecules per cell on the

1005
01:00:03.464 --> 01:00:07.084
tumor cell surface, which is above the detection threshold of our previously

1006
01:00:07.124 --> 01:00:08.543
engineered CAR T constructs.

1007
01:00:09.924 --> 01:00:13.864
We also looked for the stemness marker CD133

1008
01:00:13.904 --> 01:00:17.344
and its relationship to antigen-positive tumor cells within

1009
01:00:17.824 --> 01:00:18.844
the tumor resections.

1010
01:00:19.724 --> 01:00:23.704
And interestingly, we found that GPC2-positive tumor cells in clinical

1011
01:00:23.784 --> 01:00:26.864
samples contained a higher fraction of CD133-positive

1012
01:00:27.924 --> 01:00:28.224
cells.

1013
01:00:29.404 --> 01:00:32.844
Those also expressed higher levels of antigen density of

1014
01:00:32.904 --> 01:00:36.764
GPC2, which was not observed for B7H3 or GD2.

1015
01:00:38.524 --> 01:00:42.424
We then were wondering if these GPC2 high fractions actually

1016
01:00:42.484 --> 01:00:45.884
exhibit higher self-renewal capacities and

1017
01:00:46.564 --> 01:00:50.364
flow sorted them into high and low populations and found that the GPC2

1018
01:00:50.404 --> 01:00:52.334
high population actually was able to

1019
01:00:53.804 --> 01:00:56.264
show an increased formation of tumor spheres.

